From 504da526da41d7f891a3a4a878c601d1bfb77b96 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Neal Gompa <ngompa@fedoraproject.org>
Date: Fri, 30 Jan 2026 07:17:03 +0100
Subject: [PATCH] Allow admins to do system software management without
 password prompt

Previous versions of PackageKit permitted a local, active admin user
to install packages without a password prompt, while still requiring
the password prompt to remove packages. This doesn't make much sense.
It should be parallel.

While upstream has reconciled this and dropped the permission for
installing packages, we still want this permission in Fedora Linux.

Additionally, upstream dropped the system upgrade permission for
system administrators, which we still want as well.

Note that this change has no effect on what users are able to do,
because it only applies to admin users. The password only protects
against unlocked workstation attackers, where an attacker gains physical
access to an unlocked desktop. It's pretty weird to prevent such an
attacker from removing software, but allow installing new stuff.
It is equally odd to prevent system upgrades while permitting system
updates.

https://pagure.io/fedora-workstation/issue/233
---
 policy/org.freedesktop.packagekit.rules | 3 +++
 1 file changed, 3 insertions(+)

diff --git a/policy/org.freedesktop.packagekit.rules b/policy/org.freedesktop.packagekit.rules
index fd8374fb4..246dc16de 100644
--- a/policy/org.freedesktop.packagekit.rules
+++ b/policy/org.freedesktop.packagekit.rules
@@ -3,6 +3,9 @@
 
 polkit.addRule(function(action, subject) {
     if ((action.id == "org.freedesktop.packagekit.system-update" ||
+         action.id == "org.freedesktop.packagekit.upgrade-system" ||
+         action.id == "org.freedesktop.packagekit.package-install" ||
+         action.id == "org.freedesktop.packagekit.package-remove" ||
          action.id == "org.freedesktop.packagekit.trigger-offline-update" ||
          action.id == "org.freedesktop.packagekit.trigger-offline-upgrade") &&
          subject.active == true && subject.local == true &&
